Application Lifecycle Management (ALM) describes the complete journey of an application from planning through retirement.

Typical stages include:

* Requirements gathering
* Development
* Testing
* Deployment
* Monitoring
* Maintenance
* Retirement

For example, developers continuously improve an online banking application by releasing new features while monitoring performance and resolving production issues.

A real-life use case is software companies delivering regular feature updates through structured release processes.

A well-managed application lifecycle improves software quality and customer satisfaction.
